escription";s:110:"<p><a href="http://en.blog.wordpress.com/2009/04/24/wpcom/">Automattic / WordPress.com now has WP.com</a>!</p>";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Sat, 25 Apr 2009 01:16:49 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:4:"Matt";}s:7:"summary";s:110:"<p><a href="http://en.blog.wordpress.com/2009/04/24/wpcom/">Automattic / WordPress.com now has WP.com</a>!</p>";}i:8;a:7:{s:5:"title";s:50:"Mark Jaquith: Typographica relaunches on WordPress";s:4:"guid";s:39:"http://markjaquith.wordpress.com/?p=274";s:4:"link";s:81:"http://markjaquith.wordpress.com/2009/04/24/typographica-relaunches-on-wordpress/";s:11:"description";s:2289:"<div class="snap_preview"><br /><p><a href="http://new.typographica.org/">Typographica</a>, the excellent blog for typographical nerds, has just <a href="http://new.typographica.org/2009/on-typography/turning-the-page/">relaunched on WordPress</a> with a great new design by <a href="http://www.chrishamamoto.com/">Chris Hamamoto</a>. Asked why they switched from Movable Type to WordPress, <a href="http://new.typographica.org/2009/on-typography/turning-the-page/#comment-37961">Stephen Coles replied</a>:</p>\n<blockquote><p>For me, it seemed an obvious switch given WordPress’ wide adoption in recent years. We’ve often had trouble getting assistance with MT, whether it’s documentation or expert advice. Because WordPress is so common, the help resources and useful plugins are simply much more accessible.</p></blockquote>\n<p>WordPress&#8217; killer features are its <strong>community</strong> and its <strong>marketplace</strong>: thousands of free plugins, thousands of free themes, and hundreds of agencies and freelancers providing every possible WordPress development and support service you can imagine.</p>\n  <a rel="nofollow" href="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/markjaquith.wordpress.com/274/"><img alt="" border="0" src="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/markjaquith.wordpress.com/274/" /></a> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://feeds.wordpress.com